-- Gilts Decline as Jobless Claims Drop, U.S. Deal Optimism Grows
-- B y   N e a l   A r m s t r o n g
-- 2013-10-16T14:43:59Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-10-16/gilts-decline-as-jobless-claims-drop-u-s-deal-optimism-grows.html
U.K. government bonds fell, pushing
10-year yields to the highest level in three weeks, as a
government report showing the nationâ€™s jobless claims dropped by
the most in 16 years damped demand for safer assets.  Benchmark  gilts  declined for a third day amid speculation
U.S. Senate leaders will reach an agreement to end a fiscal
impasse and avert a government default. Separate U.K. data
showed the jobless rate was unchanged at 7.7 percent in the
three months through August amid signs the labor market is
improving. The pound slipped from a one-week high against
the dollar.  The yield on the benchmark 10-year gilt climbed four basis
points, or 0.04 percentage point, to 2.85 percent at 3:38 p.m.
London time, the highest level since Sept. 24. The 2.25 percent
bond maturing in September 2023 fell 0.345, or 3.45 pounds per
1,000-pound face amount, to 94.89.  Claims for unemployment benefit fell 41,700, the most since
June 1997, the  Office for National Statistics  said. The decline
exceeded the 25,000 median forecast in a Bloomberg survey.  The pound weakened 0.2 percent to $1.5961 after climbing to
$1.6059, the highest level since Oct. 9. The U.K. currency
dropped 0.2 percent to 84.70 pence per euro.  U.K. gilts lost 3.6 percent this year through yesterday,
according to Bloomberg World Bond Indexes. Treasuries dropped
2.8 percent and German securities declined 2.3 percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
